{"timestamp": "2025-12-01 15:57:31.874787", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — bloom-filter lab (host_1, host_2, switch_1, switch_2)\nSummary\n- End-to-end connectivity between host_1 (10.0.0.1) and host_2 (10.0.0.2) is failing: pings from host_1↔host_2 timed out.\n- Packets are reaching a bmv2 dataplane but are being dropped by the P4 program because the IPv4 forwarding table (MyIngress.ipv4_lpm) is missing matching entries (table misses → drop).\n- Root cause (high confidence): the control-plane table entries that map destination IPs to output ports were cleared (bm_mt_clear_entries) and are not present when packets are processed, so the P4 program takes its default drop action.\n\nObserved symptoms and evidence\n1) Host-level symptoms\n- get_reachability / ping attempts\n  - Attempts to ping between hosts timed out (ping commands timed out on both hosts).\n- Interface stats\n  - host_1 (10.0.0.1): eth0 shows 0 RX packets, 0 TX packets — host_1 is not receiving any packets.\n  - host_2 (10.0.0.2): eth0 shows TX packets = 4, bytes = 392 — host_2 sent packets but there is no corresponding RX on host_1.\n\n2) bmv2 dataplane logs (switch logs)\n- Thrift and initial table population\n  - Both switches started and a Thrift server was started (Thrift port 9090).\n  - Initially entries were added to MyIngress.ipv4_lpm for the /32 addresses (log entries at ~15:56:15):\n    - On one switch: LPM 0a000001 (10.0.0.1) -> MyIngress.ipv4_forward -> (port info)\n    - On the other switch: LPM 0a000002 (10.0.0.2) -> MyIngress.ipv4_forward -> (port info)\n  - These show the control-plane at some point populated forwarding entries.\n\n- Table clear event\n  - There is an explicit log line: \"bm_mt_clear_entries\" at 15:56:19.274 indicating a multi-threaded control-plane operation that cleared table entries.\n\n- Packet processing after the clear\n  - Repeated packet-processing traces (15:56:26 → 15:56:29) show incoming packets parsed as IPv4, then:\n    - Applying table 'MyIngress.ipv4_lpm': for dst 0a000001 (10.0.0.1) the table lookup is a MISS.\n    - Action entry used: MyIngress.drop\n    - The pipeline executes mark_to_drop(...) and the packet is dropped (Egress port 511, \"Dropping packet at the end of ingress\").\n  - These traces appear repeatedly for several packets (consistent behavior).\n\n3) bmv2 table/counters inspection\n- bmv2_show_tables output for MyIngress.ipv4_lpm shows the table exists but the tool output indicates \"None\" for entries (no entries present).\n- bmv2_get_counter_arrays returned empty / None (no usable counter data indicating entries/counters are gone).\n\nLocalization — where the fault is occurring\n- Fault is localized to the dataplane forwarding state (MyIngress.ipv4_lpm) on the bmv2 switch instance that is receiving packets destined to 10.0.0.1 (the logs show packets arriving on port 1 and LPM miss for dst 10.0.0.1). This implicates the switch that should forward towards host_1.\n- Both switches showed initial population of entries, but a subsequent \"bm_mt_clear_entries\" cleared tables; the effective problem is “missing forwarding entries in the switch(es)”. The symptom (host_2 sends, host_1 sees nothing) points to the switch in the path to host_1 dropping packets due to missing entries.\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- Sequence suggests:\n  1. Control-plane initially installed LPM forwarding entries for 10.0.0.1 and 10.0.0.2.\n  2. A control-plane action (bm_mt_clear_entries) cleared the entries at ~15:56:19.\n  3. After the clear, packets arriving at the switch do not find a matching MyIngress.ipv4_lpm entry (lookup returns MISS).\n  4. The P4 program’s default action for MyIngress.ipv4_lpm is to drop (MyIngress.drop), so packets are dropped in the ingress pipeline.\n- Therefore the direct root cause is missing/cleared IPv4 forwarding table entries in the bmv2 switch(es) while the P4 program’s default action is to drop. The control-plane table clear is the triggering event.\n\nImpact\n- Full loss of L2/L3 reachability between host_1 and host_2 (ICMP packets are dropped).\n- Host transmit counters increase (host_2) but receive counters on the destination (host_1) remain zero — no end-to-end traffic.\n- Bloom-filter program logic otherwise parses IPv4 packets correctly (hdr.ipv4.isValid() true) but forwarding decision cannot be made due to missing entries.\n\nRelevant timestamps / log excerpts (paraphrased)\n- 15:56:14 – Thrift server started and interfaces added.\n- 15:56:15 – Entries added to MyIngress.ipv4_lpm for 10.0.0.1 and 10.0.0.2 (table_add_entry).\n- 15:56:19.274 – bm_mt_clear_entries (table entries cleared).\n- 15:56:26 – 15:56:29 – Incoming packets processed; MyIngress.ipv4_lpm lookup for dst 0a000001 returned MISS → MyIngress.drop → packet dropped.\n\nConfidence level\n- High: Logs explicitly show entries being added then cleared, and very specific per-packet traces show table misses and the drop action. Host interface counters corroborate that packets are sent but never received.\n\nNotes / further data that would confirm details (optional)\n- Inspect current control-plane state (which process/command triggered bm_mt_clear_entries).\n- Re-run bmv2 table dump to confirm absence of LPM entries at present and to confirm whether both switches lack entries or only one.\n- If needed, capture a packet trace on the switch-to-switch link to confirm packet traversal up to the switch and the drop point.\n\n(End of report)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10819, "output_tokens": 2268, "total_tokens": 13087, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 2688}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 896}}}
